So, there is in the code 

    
    if (i==j) {
       same = true;
    }
   
You are comparing induces, not value. You have to skip comparing values at the same index, like this:

    
    if (i==j) {
       continue;
    }
    
    if (duplicateArray[i] == duplicateArray[j]) {
        same = true;
        break;
    }

Like others have said, the problem in your code is that you compare the indices (`i and j`) rather than the values (`duplicateArray[i] and duplicateArray[j]`).

Therefore, changing
```
if (i == j)
```
to
```
if (duplicateArray[i] == duplicateArray[j])
```
should fix your problem.

However, to improve your solution (which is currently an `O(n^2)` algorithm since you have two nested loops that traverse the entire array), here are several methods:

1. Return `true` when finding two equal elements:

Basically, rather than
```
same = true;
```
You can just do
```
return true;
```
since you don&#39;t care about the rest of the array; you already found a matching pair.

Although this doesn&#39;t improve the asymptotic runtime complexity, it will speed up your code by terminating early.

2. Sort the array beforehand, then compare adjacent elements:

We can use `Arrays.sort(duplicateArray);` to sort the numbers in ascending order, in only `O(n log n)` time. Now, we guarantee that equal elements are going to be next to each other, meaning that we can find the answer in `O(n)` time afterwards.

The code looks something like this (after you have received input):
```
Arrays.sort(duplicateArray);
for (int i = 1; i &lt; duplicateArray.length; i++) {
  if (duplicateArray[i] == duplicateArray[i - 1]) {
    return true;
  }
}
return false;
```
This reduces your runtime complexity to `O(n log n)`

3. Use a `HashSet`:

`HashSet`s have a `.contains()` method that runs in expected `O(1)` time. Therefore, if we add each number already traversed into a `HashSet`, we can check for equality in constant time. Traversing the array takes, therefore, `O(n)` time, so we can improve the `O(n log n)` solution.

The code would look like this (again after input):
```
Set&lt;Integer&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
for (int i = 0; i &lt; duplicateArray.length; i++) {
  if (set.contains(duplicateArray[i])) {
    return true;
  }
  set.add(duplicateArray[i]);
}
return false;
```
The only issue with this is that a `HashSet` will take extra space.

